      content:
        '<p><strong>Peter Yorke (1864-1925): A Maynooth priest in San Francisco</strong></p>\n<p>In 1949 in a series of radio lectures for Radio Eireann, the Bishop of Galway, Most Rev Dr Browne provided an overview on the careers of famous Maynooth clerics. One such person who featured in these lectures was <a href="../person/30124"><strong>Peter Yorke</strong></a>, a Galway man who led a successful struggle against anti-Catholicism and anti-trade unionism in San Francisco in the 1890s.</p>\n<p>The son of Gregory Yorke, a sea captain who owned several ships which traded between Galway and Newfoundland, and Bridget Kelly of Clew Bay, Yorke entered Maynooth in 1882 and in 1887. In Yorke\'s class were Edward Mulhern of Dromore; John Begley of Limerick; Eugene O’Growney and Denis Flynn of Meath, and Patrick Keown of Clogher, names which Bishop Browne claimed later won renown.</p>\n<p>After his appointment to the Cathedral Parish of San Francisco, Yorke came to prominence in journalism at a time when a secret society called the American Protective Association carried out violent propaganda against the Catholic Church. In 1901 when a great dispute broke out between haulage workers and employers in San Francisco Yorke championed the workers cause and fought for their rights.</p>\n<p>Editor of a number of newspapers including <em>The Monitor </em> and <em>The </em>Leader, Yorke was also a supporter of the Gaelic League and Sinn Fein. In 1899 he gave a lecture in Dublin entitled ‘The Turning of the Tide’ which was said to have been an influential moment for Irish nationalists.</p>\n<p>In recalling the career of Fr Yorke who died in 1925, the Bishop of Galway remembered a great ‘preacher, writer, and author’ concluding ‘we salute the thousands of Maynooth priests who in many lands devoted all their energies and talents to the same great cause’</p>\n<p>Today, a street in San Francisco, Peter Yorke Way, is named in his honour.</p>\n<p> </p>',
