      updatedBy: '532',
      label: 'Jack P. Hanlon',
      content:
        '<p><a href="../person/8659">John Hanlon</a> (Jack P.) (1913-1968), Dublin diocese, born in Templeogue and educated at Belvedere College before beginning his clerical studies at Clonliffe in 1932 and BA at UCD. Hanlon subsequently transferred to St. Patrick’s College Maynooth in 1934/35 and was ordained in June 1939. </p>\n<p>Having shown considerable artistic talent, Hanlon attended classes in the 1930s given by <a href="../person/87206">Mainie Jellett</a>. His work was first exhibited at the Royal Hibernian Academy (RHA) in 1934 and then at the New York World Fair in 1939. Following his ordination, he travelled to Paris to study under the Cubist painter <a href="../person/87208">André Lhote</a> - probably because of the influence of Jellett, who had studies under Lhote during the 1920s. It was during this period that his traditional style came increasingly under the influence of Modernism; a fact reflected in his role in 1943, alongside Jellett and several other Irish artists, as a founding member of the Irish Exhibition of Living Art (IELA). </p>\n<p>He would continue to exhibit his work regularly over the following decades, including at the Victor Waddington and Dawson galleries in Dublin. His work gained further international exposure through inclusion in the London Olympics Art Section in 1948 (bronze medal), and a subsequent commission to paint a mural for the Irish Pavilion at the Chicago World Fair in 1950. The 1950s and 1960s would see him complete several church commissions in Ireland and abroad, including a set of stations of the cross for the Church of Stella Maris in Downings Co. Donegal (1955), and five painted panels for the Church of the Holy Rosary, Limerick (1958).</p>\n<p>Hanlon was an enthusiastic gardener and he celebrated the beauty of nature in the many still lives of flowers he produced throughout his career. Much of his best work was in watercolour where primary importance was given to light and colour. This emphasis was also seen in his oil paintings. There was a delicacy to his palette dominated by pastel shades as well as strong primary colours, which he applied in blocks of flat colour and highlights his cubist influences. This mix of vibrancy and delicacy in his work stands in stark contrast to the much more restrained and austere nature of 1940s and 1950s Irish society.</p>\n<p>From 1945, Hanlon served as curate for several Wicklow parishes, a position that permitted him to focus more time and energy on his art. Hanlon remained a curate until illness forced him to retire to Sandycove in 1967. In August 1968 he was taken seriously ill in Tullamore, Co. Offaly and was transferred to Jervis Street Hospital where he underwent surgery, possibly for a burst appendix. He died 12 August 1968, aged 55, and was buried alongside his parents in Templeogue cemetery, Dublin.</p>\n<p>Examples of Jack P. Hanlon\'s work can be found <a href="https://www.whytes.ie/artist/father-jack-p-hanlon/15296/">here</a>.</p>\n<p><strong>Sources:</strong></p>\n<p>John Coleman, ‘A painter of living art: Jack P. Hanlon 1913-1968’ in <em>The GPA Irish Arts Review Yearbook</em> (1988), pp 222-228.</p>\n<p>Mary Catherine Reilly, ‘Hanlon, Jack P. (John Thomas)’ in <em>Dictionary of Irish Biography</em>, available <a href="https://www.dib.ie/biography/hanlon-jack-p-john-thomas-a3782%20">here</a></p>\n<p>‘Jack P. Hanlon (Irish Artist Directory)’ in <em>Adam’s Auctioneers</em>, available <a href="https://www.adams.ie/irish-artist-directory/jack-p.-hanlon-art-sold-at-auction">here</a></p>\n<p>September 2021</p>\n<p> </p>',
