      updatedBy: '532',
      label: 'Fr. John Blowick',
      content:
        '<p><a href="../person/11598">John Blowick</a> (1888-1972), Tuam diocese, born at Belcarra, Co. Mayo and educated at St. Jarlath’s College, Tuam, where he was described as ‘a good looking boy, thin, frail, self-possessed, with a kind encouraging word for new comers’. He entered St. Patrick’s College Maynooth in 1906 and was ordained in 1913. Blowick understood postgraduate studies at Maynooth in 1914, and while still a student he had the rare distinction of winning, in a public concursus, the chair of Dogmatic Theology in Maynooth (he was the last Maynooth professor selected in that way).</p>\n<p>Several years earlier, in June 1911, Blowick heard a lecture on China by the Canadian missionary, Fr. Fraser, which made a lasting impression on him. In 1916 he met <a href="../person/12150">Edward Galvin</a> and subsequently resigned his chair as professor of theology to assist Galvin in establishing a missionary society. Formal permission for the Maynooth Mission to China was given soon after by Cardinal <a href="../person/39532">Michael Logue</a> and the Archbishop of Dublin, Dr <a href="../person/8101">William Walsh</a>, with the former stating on the occasion ‘It is a consoling thing, for men whose work is almost done, to see young priests go forward willingly in such a grand work, and without having the Bishops after them with the pitchforks. I thank God that the missionary spirit is still alive’. By the time of its formal papal recognition in 1918, the society had taken on its lasting title of the <a href="../organisation/3923">Society of St. Columban</a>.</p>\n<p>Fr. Blowick remained a central figure within the society, being elected Superior General in 1919 and was amongst the first group of Columbans to travel to China in 1920 to begin their missionary work. Before travelling to China, however, Blowick had given a talk about the great need for dedicated women who would serve with the priests in ministering to the needs of the poor in China. In the audience that day was Frances Moloney, a young widow involved in efforts to relieve the poor of Dublin City. Thus, in 1922, Fr. Blowick and Moloney co-founded the Missionary Sisters of St. Columban. </p>\n<p>One of the earliest members of the missionary sisters, Patricia Sweeney, would describe Fr. Blowick as ‘a man of great missionary zeal. Yet, as we meet him in those early days we do not find him carried away in any impetuous manner by this zeal. The development of his missionary vocation and his response to the action of the Holy Spirit seem to have tempered what, to priests and students who knew him well, was a naturally impulsive character. In this new phrase of his vocational response we find a clear-thinking, far-seeing, cautious yet enthusiastic shaper of a mission. Mission needs were studied and, by systemic effort, real needs were given priority’. A letter from 1918 sums up Blowick’s approach: ‘Everything depends on initiative, and prudence to a certain point, but not too much – too much prudence will keep us from doing anything.’</p>\n<p>Returning to the Columbans, Blowick was elected Vicar-General and appointed Director in Ireland in 1924. He was again elected to the Superior General’s Council in 1947 and taught theology at the society\'s new seminary at Dalgan Park near Navan, Co. Meath. When he was in his seventies Fr. Blowick undertook a journey that took him to the principal missions of the Society. Following his death in 1972, Fr. Blowick was interred at Dalgan Park.</p>\n<p>For information on other Maynooth educated members of the society, see <a href="../resource/94486">here</a></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><strong>Sources:</strong></p>\n<p>Neil Collins (ed.), <em>Those who journey with us: deceased Columbans, 1918-2016</em>, available <a href="http://disa-app02.sixfeetup.com:8091/columban/documents/those-who-journeyed-with-us-to-2016.pdf">here</a></p>\n<p>Tom Murphy, \'Dalgan Park: Columban Missions\', available <a href="http://www.shrule.com/?page_id=1760">here</a></p>\n<p>\'Fr John Blowick\' in <em>Missionary Sisters of St. Columban</em>, available <a href="https://www.columbansisters.org/fr-john-blowick/">here</a></p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>October 2021</p>',
