      updatedBy: '72756',
      label: 'John Bannon ',
      content:
        '<h6><a href="../person/23897">John Bannon  </a>(1829-1913) Dublin diocese but born at Rooskey, county Roscommon entered St Patrick\'s College, Maynooth in 1847 and was ordained as Deacon in 1853. Sent to the archdiocese of St Louis, Missouri in the same year, where he won praise for his work. When the US Civil War broke out Bannon joined the Confederate army and was attached to the Missouri light artillery. Present at a number of battles, Bannon accompanied his unit through northern Mississippi in 1862–1863. Although taken prisoner after the Confederate defeat at Vicksburg, Bannon was soon released and travelled to Richmond where he was asked by Jefferson Davis to undertake a mission to Ireland to discourage recruitment for the Federal forces. Throughout 1864 he wrote to the <em>Nation newspaper </em>and toured the country giving political lectures. Following the end of the war Bannon entered the Jesuit novitiate at Miltown Park, Dublin (1865–6), and later studied at Louvain.  In 1867–70 he travelled Ireland as part of the Jesuit team of missionary preachers. Thereafter he founded several sodalities in Dublin. Bannon was superior of the Jesuit community in Upper Gardiner Street, Dublin (1883–9), where he spent the remainder of his life. He died 14 July 1913 at the Jesuit residence in Upper Gardiner Street and was buried in the Jesuit plot at Glasnevin cemetery.</h6>\n<h6>Courtesy of the <a href="https://www.jesuitarchives.ie/">Irish Jesuit Archives</a></h6>',
