      updatedBy: '72756',
      label: 'Daniel Cahill',
      content:
        '<p><strong><a href="../person/21328">Rev Daniel Cahill</a> </strong>(1796-1864) was born in Queen’s County (now Laois). Educated at Carlow College, Cahill entered St Patrick’s College, Maynooth in 1816. Having completed his studies in Maynooth, in 1825 he was appointed Professor of Natural Philosophy at Carlow College. Cahill was a proficient writer and edited the <em>Dublin Telegraph</em>. He was also a distinguished lecturer and a vocal opponent of the British government. In 1859 he went to the USA and lectured on Astronomy and other scientific subjects, and preached in many American and Canadian cities. He died in Boston in 1864 but his body was exhumed in 1885 and taken to Ireland, where it was buried in Glasnevin Cemetery, Dublin. His writings, entitled <em>Life, Letters, and Lectures of Rev. Dr. Cahill</em> was published in 1886.</p>',
