      updatedBy: '72756',
      label: "Daniel O'Sullivan ",
      content:
        '<p><a href="../person/6295">Daniel O’Sullivan</a> (Dómhnall O Suilleabháin)  Kerry diocese, entered St Patrick’s College, Maynooth in 1907 and was ordained in 1914. A son of Dan and Hannah O\'Sullivan of High Street, Killarney, county Kerry, following ordination O’Sullivan was sent to work at St Brendan\'s Seminary where he had been educated himself. Following a call from the Bishop of Kerry, <a href="../person/42868">John Mangan</a> for a chaplain to serve the men from the diocese who had enlisted in British war effort, O’Sullivan answered the call.</p>\n<p>On 5 July 1916, just five days after the start of the infamous Battle of the Somme, O’Sullivan was killed by shrapnel while ministering to a wounded soldier. A poem in his memory was published the following week in the <em>Kerry News</em>:</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><strong>In Memoriam</strong></p>\n<p>Captain Donal O’Sullivan chaplain to the Forces. Born in Killarney. Educated at Maynooth. Killed in France, July 1916.</p>\n<p><em>The laughter of the little days gone by. The memory of some unforgotten smile, with priestly blood spilt on the altar steps are hard to reconcile. </em></p>\n<p><em>From converse with his comrades of the school, from words of home and the caress of friends, who dreamed the Lord would snatch away so soon, an Isaac for his ends.</em></p>\n<p><em>Yet rest content, ye cloisters of Maynooth. Smile gently o’er Killarney, summer sun, for God who called to swift reward and true, first saw his work well done. </em></p>\n<p><em>And ye who nearest to the undying dead, must weep o’er vacant chair and shattered shrine, be sure that God behind this cloud doth veil, some sure august design. </em></p>\n<p><strong>L.F.K.</strong></p>',
