        label:
          'Irish Students in the Universities of Paris and Toulouse, 1573-1792',
        content:
          '<p>The newest biographical entries added to the Clericus database encompass over 1,500 Irish clerics who attended the universities of Paris and Toulouse during the period 1573 to 1792. This dataset is based on the updated 2004 version of <a href="../resource/86488">L. W. B. Brockliss and Patrick Ferté’s Prosopography of Irish clerics</a> who attended these institutions. This extensive list provides information on the education of students drawn from surviving university records, alongside additional biographical data compiled by the authors. The majority of entries (1,166) relate to the University of Paris. Toulouse’s far less complete records provide a further 263 entries, with the remaining data covering several other French universities such as at <a href="../organisation/82672">Rodez</a> and <a href="../organisation/82673">Cahors</a>.</p>\n<p>Apart from adding over 1,500 new entries to the Clericus database, this data has helped to enrich the biographical entries for several dozen individuals already present within the Clericus system, including prominent figures such as Archbishop <a href="81074">Edward Comerford</a> and <a href="76535">Cornelius Nary</a>. Added to this are several hundred individuals who were members and students of the Irish colleges at Paris and Toulouse. The former, after 1685, can be characterised as something of a national college drawing its students from all parts of Ireland, while the community of the latter college was mostly drawn from Munster, Cork in particular. For an overview of the history of the Irish College Paris, see <a href="https://www.centreculturelirlandais.com/content/files/History-CCI-English.pdf">here</a>.</p>\n<p>Other notable entries include <a href="../../person/90269">Modestus McSweeny</a>, a native of Cork and superior of the Irish College Toulouse, who was expelled by the Archbishop of Toulouse in c.1690 for inciting rebellion and disorder. McSweeny was nevertheless re-elected as superior of the Irish College and governed \'like a petty tyrant with the help of the Toulousan Parliament\' until expelled by Louis XIV of France in 1704. One interesting, if not odd example from the Irish College Paris was <a href="../../person/90409">Thady McKeogh</a> of Cashel and Emly diocese who, while serving as canon of Strasbourg in 1739, is said to have \'died after going berserk consequent on drinking tea\'.</p>\n<p>Resources:</p>\n<p>L. W. B. Brockliss and Patrick Ferté (eds), \'Prosopography of Irish Clerics in the Universities of Paris and Toulouse, 1573-1792\' in <em>Archivium Hibernicum</em>, lviii (2004), pp 7-166.</p>\n<p>L. W. B. Brockliss and Patrick Ferté (eds), \'Irish Clerics in France in the Seventeenth and Eighteenth Centuries: A Statistical Study\' in <em>Proceedings of the Royal Irish Academy: Archaeology, Culture, History, Literature</em>, 1987, lxxxviiC (1987), pp 527-572.</p>\n<p>Our sincere thanks also to Dr Liam Chambers for his assistance during the compiling of this dataset.</p>\n<p>September 2021</p>',
