        updatedBy: '72756',
        label: 'Maynooth clerics in St Louis',
        content:
          '<p>Recently added to the ‘Highlights’ section of the Clericus website were details about the career of  <a href="https://www.clericus.ie/person/23897">John Bannon</a>  and his fascinating role in the American Civil War, as chaplain to the Confederate forces. Likewise, those of<a href="https://www.clericus.ie/person/21328%20"> Daniel Cahill</a>, a noted preacher in the USA, and Andrew Eustace, just one of many ‘Maynooth’ men who ministered in St Louis throughout the nineteenth century.</p>\n<p>With thanks to Rena Schergen (MSLIS, CA, Archivist for the Archdiocese of St. Louis) a number of other clerics from St Patrick’s College, Maynooth (SPCM) have been identified as having served in the American diocese. These include <a href="../person/29375">Myles William Tobin</a> (or Tobyn) of Dublin who participated in matriculation into Humanity in 1851 at SPCM; was later ordained in St. Louis and was, for a period, pastor of SS Mary and Joseph’s church in Carondelet.</p>\n<p><a href="https://www.clericus.ie/person/23651">Thomas </a><a href="https://www.clericus.ie/person/23651">Butler</a> (1837-1897) was another of the Maynooth clerics who went to St Louis in the mid-nineteenth century and where it seems  he continued to be outspoken in his support of the Fenian movement in Ireland.  Butler died in 1897 and is buried in Cavalry Cemetery, St Louis.</p>\n<p>Other careers are less well documented, although the records held by the Archdiocese of St Louis provide a significant amount of information about their careers. Take for example, <a href="https://www.clericus.ie/person/35469">John Patrick Green (e)</a> born in Malahide, county Dublin in 1843 but who entered SPCM in 1863 for the diocese of Down and Connor. According to records in St Louis Green (e) served in Newtownards, county Down; in St Malachy’s College, Belfast as professor; and as admistrator of St Mary’s and St Malachy’s from 1878-1888. Green (e), who was ordained in 1867 by Cardinal Cullen,  arrived in St Louis in January 1893.</p>\n<p>Other Maynooth clerics who went to St Louis included three bishops, namely - <a href="../person/26003">Anthony O’Regan </a>and <a href="https://www.clericus.ie/person/34238%20">Patrick Feehan</a> , bishops of Chicago, and <a href="https://www.clericus.ie/person/38619">Peter Richard Kenrick</a> , Bishop of St Louis.</p>\n<p>In the coming weeks we will feature their careers as we delve further into the stories of Maynooth clerics in the USA.</p>',
